defaultPrevalence and nature of disability in ageindefaultg populationsdefault&#xa0;default12default&#xa0; 
defaultAgeing is associated with a higher probability of living with a disability. 
defaultWorldwide, of nearly 810 
defaultmillion people aged 60 or over (11 per cent of the world’s population), 
defaultmore than 46 per cent live with disabilities. More than 250 million
default older people experience moderate to severe disability.
default 
defaultDisabled people are ageing, and disability in older age is a consequence of accumulated health risks across a lifespan of disease, injury and chronic illness. Key causes of old-age disability are vis
defaultual impairment, hearing loss, dementia and osteoarthritis.
default 
defaultWhile the link between ageing and impairment is 
defaultinevitable, there is a less direct
default link 
defaultbetween ageing and disability. The key factors that stop impairment becoming disability are access to healthc
defaultare and an enabling environment (
defaultsuch as appropriate 
defaulthousing, care
default and
default transport).
default 
defaultHowever, these interventions are often not available in low- and middle-income countries. As a result, many older people
default, even
default with impairments such as 
defaulthearing or eyesight
default problems 
defaultthat can be resolved at little cost
default,
default 
defaultare disabled.
